{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488793"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:57:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:57:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"541"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/541"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.34,0.38,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"541"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35776"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/541"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"541"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20604"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"451"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42097"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/35776"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year-old woman presents with a painless area of redness and crusting on her left leg (see image). These findings have been present for about one year. She lives on a farm and initially thought that this was an insect bite, but this crusted area has persisted and has got a little larger. She has noticed no other patches like this elsewhere.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer medical history is notable for varicose veins in both legs, and rash under her breasts which she was recently treated for. She mentions it was \u0022very itchy\u0022, and made worse after taking hot baths.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Psoriasis","Tinea corporis","Squamous cell carcinoma","Bowen\u0027s disease (Squamous cell carcinoma in-situ)","Varicose eczema"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the skin can have a variety of morphologies. The area of crusting with central ulceration is typical of this condition. In fair-skinned older Australians, skin cancers are very common and should always be at the forefront of any diagnostic list in this group of individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be the diagnosis in this case, as this condition typically presents with pruritus of the associated lesions, a symmetrical distribution (e.g. affecting both lower limbs) and may have other signs suggestive of psoriatic arthritis (e.g. joint swelling and pain, nail pitting). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETinea\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorporis\u003C/strong\u003E classically presents with ring-shaped lesions, with a raised, scaly leading edge and central hypopigmentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBowen\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable differential for this presentation, however this condition usually presents more as flat, scaly, orange-red patches with irregular edges which grow extremely slowly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricose eczema\u003C/strong\u003E would be much more likely to be bilateral in this case, as the patient is said to have varicose veins in both lower limbs. Furthermore, this condition usually has associated pruritus of the associated plaques, and a characteristic \u0027champagne bottle\u0027 shape in the lower leg (narrowing at the ankles with induration).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Squamous cell carcinoma is more common in those with fair skin"],"references":["https://www.dermnetnz.org/topics/cutaneous-squamous-cell-carcinoma/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20604"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"541"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19908"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19908"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/29e23dff-b28f-418d-a360-8d4cc0ef6580.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/29e23dff-b28f-418d-a360-8d4cc0ef6580.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":576,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/20604"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-05-08T15:28:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-06T08:43:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"541"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35776"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group"